A Turing machine, conceptualized by Alan Turing, is basically a theoretical machine that reads a long tape of ones and zeros.

13:36.720 --> 13:37.700
Right, moving back and forth.

13:37.800 --> 13:38.160
Exactly.

13:38.560 --> 13:42.220
It moves left or right, it reads a symbol, it overwrites it with a new symbol, and moves on.

13:42.700 --> 13:46.360
The machine lives entirely exclusively in the present tense.

13:46.520 --> 13:48.460
It only knows what is on the tape right now.

13:48.760 --> 13:50.820
The text calls this out so aggressively.

13:51.440 --> 13:54.420
It says traditional languages preserve only the current state.

13:54.420 --> 13:59.400
Once 2 plus 3 becomes 5, the fact that it used to be 2 plus 3 is gone.

13:59.660 --> 14:00.140
Vanished.

